OSS in the Academic Sector

One of the main goals of our summer project is to understand who is producting open-source software (OSS) and important characteristics about them, including which sectors they are embedded within. This page focuses on the approach we took to classifying GitHub users into the academic sector as well as the prodcedures that we took to finding out which institutions they are affiliated.

First, we looked for a data source for institutions in the academic sector. We ended up using this dataset from Hipo Labs, which has the names, countries, and domain names for nearly 9,800 universities across the world. With this, we were able to identify which users are in the academic sector by looking at what self-reported organizational affiliation they have on their profile, and looking for a match in our university dataset.

However, only around 20% of our GitHub users listed any organizational affiliation on their profile, and since the input is an unvalidated, free form text field, those who did had a staggering amount of variation in how they reported it. We accounted for this in the academic sector by using regular expressions to match common abbreviations and aliases for specific academic institutions. For example, anyone whose self-reported affiliation includes the phrase "UC San Diego" is put in the same group as those including "University of California, San Diego", or "UCSD", etc. Since we were unable to find an international dataset for common university aliases, much of this had to be hard-coded. Outside of specific universities, we also included a category in the academic sector for any GitHub users who entered "Student" (or variations) as their organizational affiliation.

Besides the self-reported organizational affiliations, we also investigated email addresses as a source of information about users' affiliations. Since the university dataset from Hipo Labs includes domain names, we were able to impute the institutions for over 11,000 GitHub users based on the domain of the email address associated with their profile.

In total, we identified 40,273 users in the academic sector. Of these, 38,709 are matched to a specific institution, while 1,564 are categorized as miscellaneous students (removed from further analysis). We found that the United States is predominant: about a third of the institutions represented in our data are in the U.S., and users from those institutions make up around 55 percent of total users in the academic sector.
